[[Image:N1199-01.JPG|thumb|A Pilurs-Smith DSA-1 Miniplane built by Tracy Pilurs, on permanent display in the terminal at [[Cleveland Burke Lakefront Airport]].]]

The '''International Women's Air & Space Museum''', Inc. (IWASM) is a museum dedicated to the preservation of the history of women in [[aviation]] and [[Spaceflight|space]] and the documentation of their continuing contributions today and in the future. 

The museum began as a committee of the [[Ninety-Nines]] in order to collect historical artifacts and memorabilia of women pilots. In 1986, the International Women's Air & Space Museum opened in [[Centerville, Ohio]] in the former home of one of the [[Wright brothers]]' uncles. [[Bernice Steadman]], an [[aviator]] and member of the [[Mercury 13]], was one of the museum's co-founders.<ref name=dfpress>
{{cite news
 | first= Niraj
 | last= Warikoo
 | title= Bernice Steadman, part of NASA's 'Mercury 13' program, dies
 | work= [[Detroit Free Press]]
 | date= 2015-03-21
 | url= http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2015/03/20/berniece-steadman-mercury-astronaut-dies/25119813/
 | accessdate= 2015-04-05
 | archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/6XYwIPc72?url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2015/03/20/berniece-steadman-mercury-astronaut-dies/25119813/
 | archivedate= 2015-04-05
 | deadurl= no
}}
</ref>

Eventually IWASM outgrew its Centerville home and needed to find a new location. In 1998 the museum relocated to [[Burke Lakefront Airport]] in [[Cleveland]] where it resides in the terminal building, namely the lobby and the west concourse. As the airport is a public building, the museum is accessible every day during operating hours and charges no admission fee.

