{{Infobox Minister | name = Nenad Porges | honorific-suffix = | image = | imagesize = | office = [[Ministry of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship (Croatia)|Minister of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship]] | term_start = 15 April 1997 | term_end = 27 January 2000 | primeminister= [[Zlatko Mateša]] | predecessor = [[Davor Štern]] | successor = [[Goranko Fižulić]] | office2 = | predecessor2 = | successor2 = | term_start2 = | term_end2 = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1946|12|27|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Zagreb]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]], (now [[Croatia]]) | death_date = | death_place = | party = [[Croatian Democratic Union]] | alma_mater = [[University of Zagreb]] | residence = | spouse = | children = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = [[Croats|Croat]] }}
'''Nenad Porges''' (born 27 December 1946 in Zagreb, Croatia) is a [[Croatia]]n politician, businessman, entrepreneur and former [[Ministry of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship (Croatia)|Minister of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship]].
==Background and education== Porges was born in [[Zagreb]] to a [[Jews|Jew]]ish family who came to Zagreb from [[Vienna]] and [[Bratislava]].<ref name=jl>{{cite news|last=Stipić|first=Branka|coauthors=|title=Spanish GDP we will have in 29 years if we continue with this pace|pages=|publisher=[[Jutarnji list]]|date=2009-05-30|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/template/article/article-print.jsp?id=207417|accessdate=2010-07-03|quote= Član sam izvorne Židovske općine, ali nisam aktivan. Porgesi su bečka i bratislavska židovska obitelj... ("I am a member of the original Jewish community, but not active one. Porges are Vienna and Bratislava Jewish family...")|language=hr}}</ref><ref name=porges>{{cite news|url=http://www.porges.net/FamilyTreesBiographies/NenadPorges.html#a|title=All about Porges families|publisher=|work=www.porges.net}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were killed during the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] by the [[7th SS Volunteer Mountain Division Prinz Eugen|SS Prinz Eugen Division]], while his father's life was spared due to a fact that he was an ''essential worker'' for the [[Nazi Germany|Third Reich]].<ref name=jl/> Porges received his degrees from the [[University of Zagreb]] (a bachelor's degree in economics and a master's degree in marketing) and was a lecturer in marketing and management in postgraduate studies at the Faculty of Economics of the University of Zagreb. He was the president of the Jewish community of Zagreb until 1993, when he retired from the position.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cvitić|first=Plamenko|coauthors=|title=Ognjen Kraus - život dan medicini i židovskoj tradiciji|pages=|publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]|date=2006-04-03|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/24241/ognjen-kraus-zivot-dan-medicini-i-zidovskoj-tradiciji|accessdate=2012-05-26|trans-title=Ognjen Kraus - life dedicated to medicine and jewish tradition|archivedate=7 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68yuMH1Tn|language=hr}}</ref> Porges remains a member, though inactive, of the Jewish community in Zagreb.<ref name=jl/>
==Political and business career== As a president of the Jewish community Zagreb, Porges was a strong advocate of Croatian independence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hrsvijet.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=20553:slobodan-lang-josipoviev-govor-u-knessetu-primjer-je-lijevog-antisemitizma&catid=76:gost-kolumne&Itemid=350|title=Slobodan Lang: Josipovićev govor u Knessetu primjer je lijevog antisemitizma|publisher=|work=www.hrsvijet.net|language=Croatian}}</ref> He directed a letter to the [[World Jewish Congress]] and all affiliated Jewish organizations and institutions with the title; ''"Appeal to our Jewish brothers and sisters"''. In the letter he appealed for the recognition of Croatia and support in the [[Croatian War of Independence|Croatian War for Independence]] which was fought ''"against a brutal military force led by the [[Yugoslav People's Army|Yugoslav Army]]"''.<ref name=porges/> He served as adviser to the [[Prime Minister]] for two years. Prior to his post as adviser to the Prime Minister, Porges served as Deputy Minister of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship. In 1997 he became the Minister of Economy, Labour and Entrepreneurship in the [[Croatian Government]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10565/mjere-hnb-a-blokirale-razvoj-hrvatskog-gospodarstva|title=Mjere HNB-a blokirale razvoj hrvatskog gospodarstva|publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)]]|language=Croatian|trans-title=Croatian National Bank measures block development of Croatian economy|author=Berislav Jelinić|date=22 April 2003|archivedate=1 July 2012|accessdate=1 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68pXStPTC}}</ref> He has also worked on a number of marketing research projects and published numerous papers. In 2005 Porges was named among the one thousand most influential Croatians.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/14161/1000-najmocnijih|title=1000 najmoćnijih|author=|date=19 April 2005|accessdate=24 May 2013|publisher=|work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]|language=Croatian}}</ref> After Croatian independence Porges helped to revive [[Freemasonry]] in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arhiv.slobodnadalmacija.hr/20001105/prilozi.htm|title=Tuđman i masonstvo|author=Ivan Mužić|date=22 September 1999|accessdate=24 May 2013|publisher=|work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Croatian}}</ref>
